defaultAs of writing (
default28
defaultth
default 
defaultAugust 2013) the information is not compl
defaultete. The survey currently has 54 r
defaultesponses representing around 15
default% of local authorities
default.
default The FOI requests were made to 50 authorities
default.
default The data below needs to be read with these limitations in mind. 
default There is also some inconsistency among responses, between for example hits or visits.
default As it is 
defaulton-going
default, all findings are provisional. 
default2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhy is Open Data important? default2.1
default&#xa0; 
defaultOpen Data offers an opportunity for a number of groups. For the 
defaultpublic
default, as well as
default journalists 
defaultand
default NGOs,
default Open Data offers the chance to make government
default more transparent and open. It 
defaultalso may work to increase levels of public trust or participation, 
defaultthough these are complex areas where information can have uncertain and unpredictable effects.
default2.2
default&#xa0; 
defaultIt offers 
defaultinnovators
default the chance to re-use data for political, economic and social applications. These can go from the democratic (such as 
defaultOpenly Local
default) to the everyday (
defaultschool finder
default). Such innovations are likely to be vital bridges to wider public use and access. 
default2.3
default&#xa0; 
defaultFor 
defaultpublic authorities
default themselves, it offers the chance to be more responsive by, for example, strengthening the evidence base of policy-making or targeting resources in a particular direction. To fully realise this would require joining up and sharing data, something many authorities appear keen on but at present feel they lack the resources to do.
default2.4
default&#xa0; 
defaultOne important point to make is that Open Data is not Freedom of Information, though the two overlap. While FOI is about accessing information, Open Data is also about re-use, innovation and adaption. Seeing one as a replacement for the other risks obscuring these key differences. 
default2.5
default&#xa0; 
defaultFor Open Data, the mix of technology and political aims further confuses the meaning. One recent study spoke of how the definition itself is ‘deeply ambiguous’ as it ‘blurred the distinction between the technology of Open Data and the politics of Open Government’. 
default 
default3.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhy does the Government need an open data strategy? What should the Government’s aims be for the release of open data? Are the Government’s stated key outcomes in its Open Data Strategy the right ones? default3.1
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe core of Open Data
default reform concerns publishing ‘government data in a reusable form’.
defaultOne emerging issue is the lack of clarity over the exact aims of the government’s Transparency Agenda.
default A number of interviewees spoke of how government emphasis shifts between the ‘democratic’ aspects, using data to improve public understanding and participation, to the ‘economic’ objectives, creating re-use and economic growth. As the Shakespeare review pointed out, these aims may contradict each other and lead to 
defaultdifferent areas of government ‘pushing’ different aims.
default This is likely to be further complicated by the competing economic aims of the EU P
defaultublic 
defaultS
defaultector 
defaultI
defaultnformation
default agenda
default.
default 
default3.2
default&#xa0; 
defaultSome of the aims are also hedged with uncertainty. The NAO felt that the economic aims were based on ‘highly uncertain assumptions’ and a number of interviewees felt similarly that, while the potential was clearly there, economic aims may be difficult to realise.
default Other ideas, such as the concept of the ‘Armchair Auditors’, may also not work in the manner hoped (see below). 
default3.3
default&#xa0; 
defaultThis lack of clarity is reflected in confusion among public bodies. A 2012 survey of by the LGA found a lack of understanding
default at local level over 
defaultwho Open Data was intended for and concern that there was no clear strategy behind it.
default 
default4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIs open data presented well and of adequate quality? Are the formats of the data being published accessible, useable and understandable to the public? What metadata is needed to make releases useful? default4.1
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Public Accounts Committee (2012) highlighted concerns over how data was inconsistent, ‘raw’ and ‘very difficult to interpret’
default.
default This was for two reasons. First, information needed to be comparable across equivalent bodies. Current use of excel 
defaultfiles 
defaultwith short descriptors prevented any rigorous measurement between 
defaultthem
default. 
default4.2
default&#xa0; 
defaultSecond, information needed to be contextualised and accompanied by some form of ‘narrative’. One concern is that presentation ‘frames’ interpretation. So, for example, publication of spending data lends itself to consideration of ‘waste’ and ‘spending’ rather than understanding the effect the money has.
default A fully ‘joined up’ approach could trace spending from central government down to local authority and then to the impact. 
default4.3
default&#xa0; 
defaultThird, the 
defaultspending
default information fits with the ‘granular’ and small-scale approach associated with successful online democracy experiments.
default However, to bring about 
defaultreal accountability and participation the data also needs to be linked to clear and functioning accountability mechanisms. 
